description:
## Location
firmware/bridge-zephyr/subsys/lichen/lora_l2.c:215-221

## Finding
The `consecutive_errors` counter is an `int` that increments on each LoRa RX error:
```c
consecutive_errors++;
if (consecutive_errors > 0 && consecutive_errors % RX_ERROR_WARN_THRESHOLD == 0) {
    LOG_WRN("LoRa RX: %d consecutive errors - check hardware", consecutive_errors);
}
```

If the radio enters a persistent failure state (hardware fault, antenna disconnected), this counter will eventually overflow. After INT_MAX iterations (~2B), the counter wraps to negative values, causing the modulo check to stop triggering warnings.

## What goes wrong
In a persistent hardware failure scenario (unlikely but possible), the warning messages stop appearing after ~2 billion errors (~68 years at 1 error/second with 1s backoff). This is extremely unlikely in practice.

More realistically: the `consecutive_errors % RX_ERROR_WARN_THRESHOLD == 0` check will produce unexpected behavior around INT_MAX due to signed overflow being undefined behavior in C.

## Recommendation
Use unsigned int, or cap the counter at a maximum value:
```c
if (consecutive_errors < INT_MAX) {
    consecutive_errors++;
}
```
Or use `uint32_t` to make overflow behavior well-defined (wraps at 4B).
